The Narrative Tensor Engine (NTE):
A Unified Formal Structure for Mathematical Proofs, Narrative Arcs, Decision
Sequences, and Incompleteness
PantheonOS Project
Repository: github.com/Thanatos-Prime/pantheon-prime
DOI: 10.5281/zenodo.17755403
ABSTRACT
We introduce the Narrative Tensor Engine (NTE), a formal framework that maps
mathematical proofs, narrative arcs, decision sequences, and life trajectories onto a single
unified structure N = (S, T, R). S is the Structure Tensor encoding entities, roles, and
invariant constraints. T is the Tension Tensor encoding open questions, conflicts, goals,
and uncertainty. R is the Resolution Trajectory — the sequence of state transformations
that reduce tension to zero without violating structural invariants. We show that a narrative
'closes' when T approaches zero while S remains intact, and that this closure condition is
identical across domains: a completed mathematical proof, a resolved story, and an
executed decision sequence all satisfy the same formal criterion. We derive the NTE-Gödel
correspondence: Gödel's incompleteness theorems map directly onto the NTE structure,
with unprovable statements corresponding to permanently open tension nodes — T
components that cannot reach zero within the current S. We instantiate NTE across three
domains — a mathematical proof, a classical narrative arc, and an AI decision sequence —
demonstrating the universality of the structure. NTE provides a foundation for
cross-domain reasoning transfer, a universal benchmark for evaluating structured thought,
and a formal language for cognitive architecture.
Keywords: narrative structure, formal reasoning, Gödel incompleteness, decision theory,
cognitive architecture, unified theory of inference, tension resolution
1. Introduction
A mathematical proof and a hero's journey appear to have nothing in common. One is a sequence of
logical deductions from axioms to a conclusion. The other is a sequence of events in which a protagonist
overcomes obstacles to achieve transformation. Yet both share a deep structure: an initial state with open
tension, a sequence of moves that reduce that tension, and a terminal state in which tension is resolved.
The difference is domain, not structure.
This observation is not new. Aristotle's Poetics describes dramatic structure in terms of tension and
resolution. Polya's problem-solving heuristics apply narrative intuition to mathematics. Campbell's
monomyth identifies a single deep structure beneath diverse mythologies. What is new in this paper is the
formalization: we show that a single mathematical structure, the Narrative Tensor N = (S, T, R), captures
the essential form of all these phenomena precisely enough to be used as an analytical and computational
tool.
The implications are significant. If proofs and stories are the same object class, then techniques developed
in one domain transfer to the other. If decisions and narratives share structure, then decision quality can be
evaluated by narrative coherence criteria. If Gödel's incompleteness is a special case of permanent tension
in NTE, then the limits of formal systems can be understood through the same framework used to
understand the limits of storytelling.
Section 2 defines the NTE primitives. Section 3 defines the closure condition and beat algebra. Section 4
establishes the NTE-Gödel correspondence. Section 5 provides three full instantiations. Section 6 derives
implications for AI reasoning systems. Section 7 discusses related work and Section 8 concludes.
2. Formal Primitives of NTE
Definition 2.1 — Structure Tensor (S)
The Structure Tensor S is a triple S = (E, Ro, I) where: E is a finite set of entities (characters,
variables, agents, concepts); Ro is a set of role assignments Ro: E -> Role, defining the function
each entity plays within the system; and I is the Invariant Set — the constraints that must hold
throughout the trajectory. S defines the static frame within which the narrative operates. S may
evolve slowly (characters can change roles) but I is fixed: invariants cannot be violated without
invalidating the narrative.
Definition 2.2 — Tension Tensor (T)
The Tension Tensor T is a vector T = (Q, Co, G, U) where: Q is the set of open questions
(unresolved propositions, unanswered questions, unproven conjectures); Co is the set of active
conflicts (competing goals, contradictions, obstacles); G is the set of unachieved goals; and U is the
uncertainty measure over the current state. The tension magnitude |T| = f(|Q|, |Co|, |G|, U) where f is
domain-defined but monotonically increasing in each argument. A narrative begins with |T| > 0 and
aims for |T| = 0.
Definition 2.3 — Resolution Trajectory (R)
The Resolution Trajectory R is a finite or infinite sequence of beats: R = [b1, b2, ..., bn] where each
beat bk is an atomic state transformation bk: (S, T) -> (S', T') such that the transformation is valid
(does not violate I) and productive (|T'| <= |T| in expectation, with strict decrease required at
sufficient frequency to prevent stagnation). R is the dynamic component of NTE — the path
through state space that the narrative follows.
Definition 2.4 — Narrative Tensor N
A Narrative Tensor is the triple N = (S, T, R). N is well-formed if: (1) S is non-empty, (2) |T_0| > 0
(non-trivial initial tension), (3) every beat in R preserves I. N is complete if there exists a finite
prefix R_n of R such that |T_n| = 0. N is incomplete if no such prefix exists.
Definition 2.5 — Beat
A beat b is the atomic unit of narrative transformation. Formally: b = (pre_state, action, post_state,
delta_T, invariant_check) where pre_state is the NTE state before b, action is the transformation
applied, post_state is the resulting state, delta_T = T_post - T_pre is the tension change (negative
values indicate resolution), and invariant_check: I -> {pass, fail} confirms constraint satisfaction. A
beat that fails invariant_check is inadmissible and cannot be appended to R.
3. Closure Condition and Beat Algebra
Definition 3.1 — Narrative Closure
A Narrative Tensor N = (S, T, R) achieves closure at beat n if and only if: (1) |T_n| = 0 — all
tension components are resolved; and (2) For all k <= n, invariant_check(bk, I) = pass — no
invariant was violated along the trajectory. Closure is the formal analog of: proof completion in
mathematics, narrative resolution in fiction, decision execution in governance, and life meaning in
existential terms.
Theorem 3.1 — Closure Equivalence
Let N_proof be an NTE instantiation of a mathematical proof, N_story be an NTE instantiation
of a narrative arc, and N_decision be an NTE instantiation of a decision sequence. Then
N_proof, N_story, and N_decision achieve closure under the identical formal condition: |T_n| =
0 with all invariants preserved. The closure condition is domain-invariant.
Proof: By Definition 3.1, closure is defined purely in terms of T and I, which are defined identically
across all N instantiations regardless of domain. The domain determines the content of S, T, and R
— not the closure condition itself. Therefore closure is domain-invariant. QED.
3.2 Beat Algebra
Beats compose under sequential application. Let b1 and b2 be admissible beats. Then b1 * b2 denotes
sequential composition, defined as: apply b1 to (S, T), obtain (S', T'), then apply b2 to (S', T').
Composition is associative but not commutative — beat order matters. The identity beat b_id maps (S, T)
to itself with delta_T = 0. Beats with delta_T > 0 are called tension-increasing (complications, reversals,
new questions). Beats with delta_T < 0 are tension-resolving (answers, victories, proofs). A
well-constructed R alternates these types, with net negative delta_T over the full trajectory.
The beat algebra enables formal comparison of narratives: two N instances are isomorphic if there exists a
structure-preserving bijection between their beat sequences that maps tension changes onto tension
changes. This is the formal basis for the claim that a Euclidean proof and a detective story are isomorphic
objects.
4. The NTE-Gödel Correspondence
We now establish the most significant theoretical result of this paper: Gödel's incompleteness theorems are
a special case of NTE incompleteness.
4.1 Background
Gödel's First Incompleteness Theorem (1931) states that any consistent formal system F capable of
expressing basic arithmetic contains statements that are true but unprovable within F. His Second
Incompleteness Theorem states that such a system cannot prove its own consistency. These results
establish permanent limits on formal reasoning — there exist questions that a system cannot resolve from
within itself.
4.2 The Correspondence
Definition 4.1 — Gödel Statement as NTE Tension Node
Let F be a consistent formal system. Construct N_F = (S_F, T_F, R_F) where: S_F = (axioms of F,
inference rules of F, consistency of F); T_F = set of all open conjectures provable or refutable
within F; R_F = the sequence of proofs constructed within F. A Gödel statement G_F is a statement
that is true but unprovable within F. In NTE terms, G_F is a tension node in T_F that cannot be
reduced to zero by any admissible beat in R_F — i.e., no sequence of inference steps within F can
close this tension component.
Theorem 4.1 — NTE-Gödel Correspondence
Let F be a consistent formal system satisfying Gödel's conditions. Then N_F is an incomplete
Narrative Tensor: there exist tension components in T_F that cannot be resolved by any finite
R_F. Furthermore, the Gödel statement G_F corresponds exactly to a permanently open tension
node — a component of T_F for which no admissible beat exists within S_F. The system can be
extended (S_F -> S_F') by adding G_F as a new axiom, which resolves this tension node but
necessarily creates new permanently open nodes in T_F'.
Proof sketch: Gödel's construction produces G_F such that: (a) G_F is true (in the standard
model), meaning the tension it represents is real; and (b) G_F is unprovable within F, meaning no
beat sequence in R_F reduces its tension to zero. This is precisely the NTE definition of a
permanently open tension node. Adding G_F as an axiom extends S_F, but by Gödel's second
theorem, the extended system F' has its own Gödel statement G_F', which is a new permanently
open tension node in T_F'. The hierarchy is infinite. QED.
4.3 Implications of the Correspondence
The NTE-Gödel correspondence has three significant implications.
Incompleteness is universal. Because NTE applies to all domains, the existence of permanently open
tension nodes is not a pathology of mathematics — it is a structural feature of any sufficiently expressive
system. Stories can have permanently open questions. Decisions can have permanently unresolvable
tensions. Life arcs can have irreducible uncertainty. These are not failures; they are Gödelian features of
the domain.
Extension is always possible. Just as adding G_F as an axiom extends F while preserving consistency,
any narrative system can be extended by incorporating its open tension nodes as new structural elements.
This is the formal basis for sequels, appendices, research programs, and ongoing governance frameworks.
Self-reference generates incompleteness. Gödel's construction relies on self-reference: G_F says 'I am
not provable.' In NTE terms, a narrative that contains a beat referencing its own closure condition will
necessarily produce a permanently open tension node. Self-referential systems are structurally incomplete
— this is a feature, not a bug.
5. Three Domain Instantiations
We now instantiate NTE across three domains, demonstrating that the same formal structure describes
each.
5.1 Instantiation I: Euclid's Proof of Infinite Primes
